/**************************************************************************\
* 									   *
*  			HISTORY of user-visible changes			   *
* 									   *
\**************************************************************************/

1.8c            (95/12/08)              color usage reduction

    DISTRIBUTION:

      - colors cleaned in all xpm files to use less colors. Use only colors in
        rgb.txt, and some digitilized ones were reduced by hand

    BUGS CORRECTED:

      - "Henry S. Thompson" <ht@cogsci.ed.ac.uk>: patches to compile on
        freebsd

    STANDARD PROFILE:
   
      - "pack icon" menu item now raises all icons too

      - in distributed data/.profile.gwm: see the section "Netscape" that
        adds behaviors to netscape icons:
          - selecting an URL and control-middle-mouse on a netscape icon will
	    make this netscape instance open the URL
          - selecting an URL and control-left-mouse or control-alt-middle-mouse
	    will create a new netscape window on the URL


1.8b            (95/09/22)		bug fixes

    COMPATIBLE ENHANCEMENTS:

      - window-icon-name could only be read, not set. Now you can set it, it
        will modify the window hint just like window-name does.

    STANDARD PROFILE:
   
      - New decoration: timeout-window
        timeout-win allows you to specify a command to be applied to a window 
        N seconds after its creation. Very useful to get rid of unwanted pop-ups
        such as XMH mime requesters each time I go into a mail error message...

      - virtual screen: wallpaper is changed too when going to a room via the 
        map

    MWM PROFILE:

      - TRUE MWM look by Anders, with his recursive bars.

    BUGS CORRECTED:

      - Anders Holst <aho@nada.kth.se>:
        virtual-pan.gwm float.gwm:
        patches to fix xlock problems (float windows race condition)
	vtwm-menu.gwm vtwm-window.gwm:
        treatment of color focus, which were not so good before

      - data/simple-ed-win.gwm: old code was limiting the size of plugs 
        in titlebar.

      - Naoki Hamada <nao@sbl.cl.nec.co.jp>: 
        potential problem in GC fixed (call to GC before its initialisation)

      - bugs to the twm profile fixed

    DISTRIBUTION:
 
      - data/wallpaper.gwm new file (old but forgot to include in distrib) 
        code to add wallpaper effects to the dvrooms package.

      - documents the fact that gwm seems to work on alpha if compiled 
        with -taso

    CONTRIBUTED SOFTWARE:
   
      - contrib/gwmsend: now appends property instead of overriding it

    DOCUMENTATION:
   
      - of timeout-win, in standard profile chapter.


1.8a            (95/07/03)	        optional logging

    A small fix, logging by sending an udppacket is now disablable at run
    time by setting the environment variables NO_GWM_LOG or NO_KOALA_SPY to
    disable this feature without recompilation, for users who get pre-compiled
    binaries.


1.8		(95/06/30)		recursive non-rectangular bars

    1.8 can be seen as the "final edition" of the current gwm. It "cleans the
    attic" by including all patches and fixes that has been sent to me by the
    active gwm community since the last major release, 1.7o in September 93,
    it provides powerful new features to implement looks and feels never seen
    in any previous WM, and provides a stable C base for future developments, as
    I embark into re-vamping the C layer into a better but incompatible
    version, "kwm" (Koala Window Manager), the name not being gwm v2 to stress
    the incompatibility of the profiles.

    NEW FEATURES:

      - A *big* addition by Anders Holst <aho@nada.kth.se>! Now bars can have
        sub-bars, recursing indefinitely, alternatively horizontal and
        vertical, not unlike the hbox/vbox geometry management system of
	TeX. This should allow building profiles to emulate *completly* any
	window manager look

      - Also by Anders, bars can be non-rectangular. If their background is set
        to t, this means a totally transparent background. And bars can have
	arbitrary shaped backgrounds (shaped tiles)

      - I added a small module to send me an upd packet every day by every
        running gwm so that I can have some idea of the use, and more
        importantly propagation of new versions. This will only send your
        hostname, and will silently fail if the network is not present. You can
        either disable this by -DNO_GWM_LOG, or better do a 
        -DGWM_LOG_ID="\"a_name_of_your_setup\"" if you dont want me to log this
        information, that I wont publish but will help me to better have a
        feeling for the use of gwm.
        see spy.c and GWM_log function in gwm.c, module done by
        Cedric.Beust@sophia.inria.fr, http://www.inria.fr/koala/beust.html

      - Sven Wischnowsky <oberon@cs.tu-berlin.de>:
        patch for the gwm.c file which adds two new options:
        -I: this one makes gwm still read its stdin (and, of course, 
	    evaluate it) once running. You can thus type interactive commands
	    to gwm in the xterm running a gwm -I
        -P: together with -I makes gwm print a simple prompt showing the
            number of currently open parentheses
        see file data/emacs-mode.readme for details

    COMPATIBLE ENHANCEMENTS:

      -  border-on-shaped new global variable to allow border on shaped
         windows. If a window is shaped (non-rectangular), gwm by default
	 removes the border around its window frames, setting this variable to
	 t inhibits this behavior.

    INCOMPATIBILITIES WITH PREVIOUS PROFILES:

      - (bar-make ()), and in fact (bar-make () ... ()) was equivalent to
        (bar-make), but it is no longuer the case, as now (bar-make ()) means
	a really extensible bar with the new non-rectangular bar system.
	*** You *MUST* relace all the occurences of (bar-make ()) by
	(bar-make) in your profiles.	

      - a tiny detail: by default now, bar-max-widths is set by default to
        1000 instead of 20, as this limit could cause unexpected behaviors
	with the newers decorations allowed by the new recursive
	non-rectangular bars

    STANDARD PROFILE:

      Additions of options to the simple-win and simple-icon
      packages to benefit from the non-rectangular bars:
      - stretch option to simple-icon to allow legends to expand past the
	icon image (plug) itself, "a la" macintosh.
	stretch can be "top", "left", "right", "bottom" to tell which side
	will stretch, default is both (centered) for other non-nil values.
	(setq simple-icon.stretch t) will make it the default.
      - legend option can be "top", "left", "right", "bottom" to specify where
        the legend should be wrt the icon. legend can still be set to t to
	mean "bottom" for backwards compatibility. Works for simple-win and
	simple-icon.
	e.g: (customize simple-icon any XTerm legend "left")
      - label option can be a lambda function that will be applied to the
        window name (simple-win) or icon name (simple-icon) to return the
	string that will be used in the title. Can be used to remove the 
	"@ host" from emacs titles or remove the "Netscape: " prepended by
	netscape to all its windows
        e.g: to supress the Netscape: in netscape icon titles
        (customize simple-icon any Netscape
           label (lambdaq (s) (match "Netscape: \\(.*\\)$" s 1)))
      - simple-win have two options lpad and rpad which gives the amount of
        padding (nils in bars) before and after the label. each must be a
	number.
      - tile can be set to the background of the title bar of simple-win and
        term-icon to make disappear the bar, leaving only the label.

      - Sample "diagonal" definitions included in data/placements.gwm (last
        lines)  by Michael A. Patton <map@bbn.com>. gives a rows.diag-ul and
	rows.diag-ur to place windows/icon ins diagonales along the screen
	from upper left and right corners.

      - Simple virtual screen package base on the one done by Anders for 
        vtwm.gwm. Do a (load "std-virtual.gwm") to get it.

    MWM PROFILE:

      - various bug fixes

    TWM PROFILE:

      - another big contribution by Anders Holst <aho@nada.kth.se>, the vtwm
        profile, that uses sub-modules for virtual screen (virtual.gwm) and
	icon manager (vtwm-icon-mgr.gwm) than could be used with other gwm
	profiles.
	run it by gwm -f vtwmo

    DISTRIBUTION:

      - *** XPM LIBRARY NO MORE INCLUDED! ***
        Xpm is becoming a de facto standard. Is adopted by Motif 2.0 and COSE
        CDE and many other packages (TCL/Tk, xemacs...) so you SHOULD have it
        installed somewhere. if not, compile it. With its inclusion in CDE 1.0,
        its API is freezed so there wont be any compatibility problems.
	Xpm can be found on ftp.x.org and mirrors or koala.inria.fr:/pub/xpm

      - new FTP locations:
        Europe: koala.inria.fr:/pub/gwm/
        USA:    ftp.x.org:/contrib/window_managers/   (and its worldwide mirrors)

      - all goodies which are not just loadable gwm scripts are now in the
        contrib/ subdirectory. There you will find emacs modes, systems to
	interactively execute Wool code in a running gwm from an xterm or an
	emacs buffer, and the rxterm scripts to remotely execute xterms.
	None of this packages is automatically compiled and/or installed,
	you'll have to do this by hand.

      - the rxterm script is not installed anymore, as many sites has already
        this sort of mecanism already installed

    BUGS CORRECTED:

      - many, many bug fixes by Anders Holst <aho@nada.kth.se>. And of course,
        by a lot of gwm users whose names are detailed in revisions.c

      - now a warning is issued if an application maps its window with an
        incorrect initial_state hint, but the window is mapped nonetheless.

      - some problems with XV window migration fixed, and the unfixable
        documented in doc/KNOWN_BUGS

      - all known memory leaks fixed (some on xpm loading, menu creations, 
        lambda deletions, list-of-windows)

      - if errors occured while decorating a window or an icon, the window
        could become unmapped

      - ejb@ERA.COM (E. Jay Berkenbilt): patches for time on SYSV machines

      - now displays correctly internationalized texts (compounds strings) in
        window and icon names

      - some roundoff errors occured when resizing windows at screen 
        boundaries when confine-windows was set

   CHANGES TO THE DOC:

      - Michael Welsh Duggan <md5i+@andrew.cmu.edu>: corrections to gwm doc

      - Documentation for the new bar-make, and the new simple-win and
        simple-icon modes


1.7o		(93/09/03)		non-rectangular icons

    COMPATIBLE ENHANCEMENTS:

      - gwm now completely supports non-rectangular icons, either from ICCCM
        hints set by the applications (icon mask hint in WM_HINTS), or by
	using XPM color pixmap files for the icon center plugs, and they can
	be modified on the fly.

      - new variable: xpm-closeness. If set, sets the "closeness" XPM value
        when loading XPM file. This allows to search the colormap for already 
        allocated colors "close enough" when the colormap is full. You can
	thus use sperb colorful icons without any restraints!
	Defaults to 40000, which is the recommended XPM value. See the XPM
	documentation for full explanation.

      - -k and -K new command line options:
	Dan Griscom <griscom@media.mit.edu>:
	It's the "-k pid" option, which takes a process id as an
	argument. When gwm has finished initializing, it sends a signal(SIGALRM
	by default) to the given process. So, if you do the following lines:
	sleep 15 & pid=$!
	gwm -k $pid &
	wait $pid
	then your init shell script will pause until gwm has finished 
	initializing.
	-K signal_num sets the signal number to signal_num instead of
	SIGALRM (14)

      - term-icon-xpm:
        Icon decoration, like term-icon, but frames the icon name with 8 XPM 
	icons, instead of bitmaps, allowing you great looks!. Just try:
	  ;; your dominant screen background color
	  (setq screen-background (color-make "lightseagreen")) 
          (set-icon-window XTerm
	    (term-icon-xpm "xterm3" pop-item.font
	      (color-make "DarkSlateGrey")
	      (color-make "yellow")))

      - xpm-icon:
        an icon decoration allowing for using colorful non-rectangular icons
        (xpm files), choosen by the state of the application, and updated 
	on icon pixmap or icon/window name change. See file data/xpm-icon.gwm
	As far as I know, gwm is the only X WM to allow you to have a colored,
	non rectangular icon of xmh changing when new mail arrives...

    MWM PROFILE:

      - I fixed f.exec to allow arguments in commands in a natural way, now
        (f.exec "xedit foo") works, no need to type (f.exec "xedit" "foo")

      -  mwm: Meta-X no longer maximizes the window by default, since it is 
         annoying for emacs users (ed.duomo@lambada.oit.unc.edu)

    DISTRIBUTION:

      - new room package: wbrooms.gwm, contributed by William Burdick
        <burdick@octopus.ecn.purdue.edu>. The idea is like dvrooms, except 
	that a room is a bar of buttons, and they have a nice 3D look.

      - XPM lib upgraded to the most recent one, 3.2g (performance gains)

      - generated LEX & YACC parsers are included for users without lex&yacc
        (most notably LINUX, flex and bison do not work with gwm).
	see directory gwm-parsers.

    BUGS CORRECTED:

      - Calvin Clark <ckclark@MIT.EDU>:
        error in grab lists should not abort decoration
	
      - errors in icon decoration could leave the main window unmapped

      - more fixes to WM_TAKE_FOCUS Protocol: fix by David Hogan 
        <dhog@cs.su.oz.au>, reported by John Mackin <john@civil.su.oz.au>.
	Other fixes by rjc@cogsci.edinburgh.ac.uk (Richard Caley).

      - simple-win.gwm: typo was preventing color chnage of label with focus-in
        bug fix by: Tom Yu <tlyu@MIT.EDU>

      - "Henry S. Thompson" <ht@cogsci.edinburgh.ac.uk>
  	(pixmap-make width heigth) now take into account tile if it exists

      - patches for compiling with flex by Olaf Kirch (on linux)
        <okir@mathematik.th-darmstadt.de>. See revision.c.

      - various bug fixes to the code by: (see revision.c for full details)
        caret@sword.eng.pyramid.com (Neil Russell)
	"Mike Marques" <mike@ccs.yorku.ca>
	kenw%bilbo@ihs.com (Ken Weinert)
	dwight@toolucky.llnl.gov ( Dwight Shih )
	Julian Gosnell <jules@tomen-ele.co.jp>
	Steven Charlton <steven@cs.ualberta.ca>
	Reg Quinton <reggers@julian.uwo.ca>
	Michael A. Patton <MAP@lcs.mit.edu>


1.7n		(92/08/28)		bugs

    BUGS CORRECTED:

      - there were still problems with some idraw pop-ups (file selectors),
        due to bugs in idraw WM_HINTS positioning. fixed.

      - some windows could be left unmapped in some cases. problem discovered
        by Michael A. Patton <MAP@lcs.mit.edu>

      - -DNO_STRUCTURE_OFFSETS compilation flag to be able to compile
         wl_event.c on picky compilers (DECstations, apollo)

    DISTRIBUTION:

      - data/move-opaque.gwm: call to process-exposes to avoid crashes
	fix provided by tsm@cs.brown.edu (Timothy Miller)


1.7m		(92/08/10)		bugs

    BUGS CORRECTED:

      - some memory bugs, found by using the wonderful purify utility. Get a
        demo version of purify by mailing to support@pure.com

      - bad implementation of the WM_TAKE_FOCUS ICCCM protocol corrected. bug
        shown with lucid emacs

      - the new "map-on-raise" flag couldn't be turned off

      - cstruble@gnu.ai.mit.edu (Craig Struble) fixed a short/int comparison
        problem

      - load: on absolute pathnames, do not add extensions
        check that extension is not already there before adding it

      - Calvin Clark <ckclark@mit.edu>: bad handling of the sibling field in
        ConfigureRequest events

    DISTRIBUTION:

      - gwm-buffer.el in data dir by Mike Fletcher <fletch@cad.gatech.edu>
        an interactive wool mode (remotely executed by the running gwm)
	under emacs
        Note: this package was also called wool-mode.el (name that I would
	reserve to a package to indent wool) or gwm-mode.wl. I renames it with
	the same name as its main function...

      - blk@vanity.mitre.org (Brian L. Kahn): drop-menus packages for use 
        with epoch. files in data/:
        drop-menus.doc drop-menus.gwm style.gwm widgets.el widgets.gwm

        I began writing more customizable versions. Look at:
        em-widgets.gwm em-drop-menus.gwm em-example.gwm

      - Doug Bogia <bogia@cs.uiuc.edu>: no more button bindings overriding by
        the mon-keys.gwm package

    MWM PROFILE:

      - Glen Whitney <gwhitney@math.ucla.edu>: new version of the mwm emulator.
        mwm files overriden, but saved in mwm-emul-1.0.tar.Z in ftp sites
        see mwm-emulation.txt

    COMPATIBLE ENHANCEMENTS:

      - New context flag for windows: ignore-take-focus (default ()). If set,
        the WM_TAKE_FOCUS protocol is never used for the window, even if it
	is set by the window

    CHANGES TO THE DOC: none


1.7l		(92/03/02)		bugs + framemaker support

    BUGS CORRECTED:

      - gwm now ignores directories when loading files. if you had a directory
        named "utils" for instance in your GWMPATH, gwm would not load 
	"utils.gwm".

      - some changes for compiling on stellar (Timothy Miller)

    STANDARD PROFILE:

      - .profile.gwm now loads "framemaker.gwm"

      - (setq confine-windows t) was overriden by unconf-move in .profile.gwm
    	Doug Bogia <bogia@cs.uiuc.edu>

      - standard .profile now loads "my-menus.gwm" for user-specific
        customisation (so that the standard profile can be shared)

    TWM PROFILE:

      - bugs to twm profile corrected (would core dump after a while).
	Dag Diesen <dagdis@ifi.uio.no>

    DISTRIBUTION:

      - new flag "UseInstalledXpm" in Imakefile to use already installed XPM 
	library
	klute@irb.informatik.uni-dortmund.de (Rainer Klute)

      - new file: fast.gwm (for gwm -f fast), to make a very primitive, fast
	starting WM, by 
	ejb@era.com (Jay Berkenbilt)

      - epoch.gwm was obsolete, updated.

      - button mapping removed from mon-keys.gwm
    	Doug Bogia <bogia@cs.uiuc.edu>

    COMPATIBLE ENHANCEMENTS:

      - never-warp-pointer variable to disable all calls to warp pointer
        tim@stanley.cis.brown.edu (Timothy Miller)

      - map-on-raise flag interpreted by decoration to know if we must 
	de-iconify a window if the client raises it. 
	This is for FrameMaker, which doesn't expect some of its dialogs to
	ever be iconified, and thus only raises them when you request them.
	this flag on FrameMaker decos de-iconify them also.

    CHANGES TO THE DOC:

      - new entries:
        never-warp-pointer, map-on-raise, fast.gwm, framemaker.gwm.


1.7k		(92/02/12)		bugs

    BUGS CORRECTED:

      - 'background key in meter function was ignored
	(bug report from "Mike Marques" <mike@apex.yorku.ca>)

      - (property-change any) was not working

      - Michael Bloom <mb@ttidca.tti.com> patches for interviews

      - window-group has now sanity checks to always return a list or ().
	FrameMaker was setting bad hints that could confuse gwm

      - a internal random bug on GC was corrected, might have been the bug
        inducing bus errors on some move-window calls.

    STANDARD PROFILE:

      - new resources for simple-icon:
	simple-icon.plug-name forces the icon name
	simple-icon.no-center-plug forces icon to ignore application pixmap

    DISTRIBUTION:

      - data/en-recover.gwm utility code from Eyvind Ness <eyvind@hrp.no>
	included in distrib. code used to map back lost windows.

      - data/framemaker.gwm is a sample of special utilities coded to manage
	framemaker windows

    COMPATIBLE ENHANCEMENTS:

      - Philippe Kaplan's additions of hooks for external window management
        (not yet documented, might be changed, notably to better implement the
	ICCCM v2). Provides access to ClientMessages by the functions:

	(client-message atom) waits for a client message of type atom

	(current-event-data) returns a 5-element list made with the contents of
	the client message (if numeric) or a string.

	(send-client-message atom args...) sends a client message with tag
	atom and with (at most 5) numeric args to the current window, or a
	string arguments (then first 20 chars are sent).

    CHANGES TO THE DOC:

      - the doc is untouched.


